metadata.name: Cellular Skyscrapers #171
metadata.description:
A "Cellular Skyscraper" originates from a 15x15 grid with 15x3 cells randomly assigned the 'alive' state. According to the cellular automaton rule chosen from the transaction hash 24 new generations are calculated and placed on top of each other.

There are four different rules available (listed in Golly notation) all based on the Moore neighbourhood: 

B3/S23 (Game of Life)
B36/S125 (2x2)
B368/S245 (Morley)
B3/S234 (didn't find a name for it but produces interesting large structures)

After all generations have been calculated the algorithm searches through the complete 3D grid to find the one structure consisting of the most connected alive cells - cells are connected when they have at least one alive neighbour in any of the three axis.

Features are cell count, height, highlight color, ca rule and antenna count.

Extra: press 'd' to download the structure as a .gltf file to import into Blender or other software.
 
Enjoy!

metadata.name: Idem Locus #63
metadata.description:
The artist of this art piece found its inspiration not in an individual artist, but rather in the aesthetic of an entire era - the engravings from the Late Middle Ages and the early Renaissance.

"Idem Locus" (Latin for "The Same Place") was conceived as a result of delving into the engravings of the 15th and 16th centuries, contrasting the portrayed locations with their contemporary counterparts. 

Idem Locus was part of the Blind Gallery x Feral File Vistas Edition
For more information, visit https://www.blindgallery.xyz/

metadata.name: Dynamic generations #154
metadata.description:
A classic cellular automata updates its state with a static rule based on the state of its neighbor.

This collection was created with cellular automata with an extension of that idea. Here the state and the rule are updated based on the state of its neighbor, here the rule changes in every iteration, here the rule is dynamic.

That change moves cellular automata to another level of complexity.

metadata.name: This is Not an Image #35
metadata.description:
When you see a piece of generative art, you are looking at a meta-message, an image whose value is not of form but of subtext. These images are a collision and reformation of ideas and conceptual histories between artists Nudoru and Sub Net. This dichotomy reminds us of the painting "The Treachery of Images" by René Magritte, where he paints a picture of a pipe but states underneath, "ceci n'est pas une pipe" (This is not a pipe), meaning that there is a schism between what a thing is and what it represents. What is unique about these works go beyond the images and text combinations themselves. It is about how images create new thoughts not by not pretending to be completely novel but that builds upon one another in a system of complex synthesis.

This token is part of the Floor Exhibit co-curated by the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC and Fort Gallery NFT.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press' p' to pause/resume.
Press' s' to save a screenshot. The image size is 2357 × 3000px.

metadata.name: plaid-waves.gif #47
metadata.description:
A pixelated continuation of my obsession with artificially blended colors.

plaid-waves.gif is 32 x 32 pixels, made of two primary color cycle layers, two highlight layers and almost 200 BILLION possible variations!

Export the result as a gif with a single button:

* First you must be viewing the NFT on IPFS

Keyboard:
• [i] Show info about the loop length in seconds
• [g] Export GIF or PNG (depending on if work is still or animated)
• [x|d] Alternate export keys. "eXport" and "Download"

Mobile:
• [double tap] Open export screen. See loop length in seconds and an export button.


~~~

Project built using the FROSTxHASH template by Matthew Seremet (frostbitten.tez). Builder version 0.48. Available at https://frostxhash.clxn.art

metadata.name: Until biodiversity rains #102
metadata.description:
Audiovisual generative artwork. 

In the interpretation of biological organisms, which break paradigms by doing something different, to adapt to changes and be able to survive, paths emerge to be imitated by so many, and make life flow. The development of the work is a metaphor for those paths full of ingenuity and risk, where colorful organisms in rows open trails, sliding like subtle drops, with sophisticated turns and elastic jumps.

Some alternative paths usually hide a message along the way. Literally, one could find and read phrases in relation to biodiversity and its importance. Although it is more common to ignore them, sometimes not respect them, or what is worse, forget them. Even so, in an exacerbated insistence, here, audiovisual organizations seem to be repeating themselves, “until biodiversity rains”, and variety exploits so that ecosystems finally go it alone.


Relationship between visuals and sounds:
Biological organisms of different colors follow a path. They move forward, change shape, stop, turn. Always one after the other. At certain moments, they stretch and jump and sounds emerge.

Towards the edges of the canvas, the jumps are translated into cello sounds, mainly pizzicatos. Towards the center, the piano. From the main jumps emerges a kind of melody played by a pseudo-theremin-synth, characterized by flyaway melodies with glissant.


This artwork is 100% code, made in p5.js + tone.js.

[ Click ]  -> sound ON / OFF
[ s ] -> save 2160x2160px (in live view)
[ f ] -> fullscreen
[ p ] -> pause / play 

Note: This artwork is an animated piece, and requires a powerful GPU for optimal real-time playback. It is important to note that it may not run properly on mobile devices, especially not high-end ones.
It is recommended to run the piece in a new window from the “open” button.
